    <main><div class='container-fluid' id='dict_container'>
      <h1><span class='badge badge-primary'>character in C++</span></h1>
      <div class='container-fluid'>
          <pre id='word_content' style='white-space: pre-wrap;'>Char is defined by C++ to always be 1 byte in size. By default, a char may be signed or unsigned (though it&#039;s usually signed). If you&#039;re using chars to hold ASCII characters, you don&#039;t need to specify a sign (since both signed and unsigned chars can hold values between 0 and 127).
```
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
 
int main()
{
    char ch1{ &#039;a&#039; }; // (preferred)
    std::cout &lt;&lt; ch1; // cout prints a character
 
    char ch2{ 98 }; // code point for &#039;b&#039; (not preferred)
    std::cout &lt;&lt; ch2; // cout prints a character (&#039;b&#039;)
 
 
    return 0;
}
```</pre>
      </div>
